<!--
  Driver-side manifest. AGP merges this into the synthesized test manifest under
  testApplicationId = com.rudderstack.testapp.driver.

  Intentionally minimal at Step 4: cross-package broadcast and ContentProvider
  reads need nothing here. The dynamic EVENT receiver registers programmatically
  in BroadcastTransport.

  ## Known gap, deferred to Step 6: destructive-op survival

  The two-APK split (§11) gives the driver its own applicationId, but the
  instrumentation framework binds its lifecycle to <instrumentation
  android:targetPackage>, which AGP defaults to the SUT's applicationId. So
  `pm clear com.rudderstack.testapp`, `am force-stop`, or `am kill` crash the
  instrumentation even though the driver runs in its own process.

  Pointing targetPackage at the driver itself breaks the AGP-managed classpath
  sharing between SUT and test APKs (kotlin-stdlib goes missing at app load,
  among other things). The fix needs both a manifest rewrite *and* test-APK
  packaging changes to make it self-contained — non-trivial AGP work that
  Step 4 isn't the right place for.

  Step 6 wires lifecycle Step types (Background, Foreground, Kill, ForceStop,
  ColdStart, ClearAppData) into the interpreter. The destructive ones won't be
  callable from inside an @Test until this is solved. Step 4's AdbLifecycleControl
  class is correct in shape — only the destructive *tests* are deferred.
-->
<manifest xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android" />
